post_text:
DISTRICT UPDATE

Ortonville School Families,

I wished to reach out to you following Governor Walz's press conference today. Our Ortonville Fall Planning Team is excited to receive the Governor's "Safe Learning Plan" which provides local control (with MDH guidance) on the "Return to School" for the upcoming year. Our team will be meeting again for a full day of planning tomorrow. We anticipate having our plan finalized no later than noon on Monday followed by a presentation to staff at 2:00 PM. We plan to share this out to families on Monday, August 3rd following Board adoption. Today was a great day. I'm proud of how our Governor and his leadership team layed out a supportive and comprehensive plan. Please know, our plan has the safety of all staff & students in mind. I'm proud of our committee work thus far and I know families will appreciate their efforts. We look forward to sharing this out Monday night. Please keep in mind, your safe choices today can keep our kids in front of their teachers. We're in this together!

Cory Larson, Superintendent

post_text:
Effective 7/25/2020, per governor's Executive Order 20-81, Face Mask/Covering must be worn to enter the school.

Key Points:

Visitors, Staff, and students will be required to wear masks while in school buildings or riding on school transportation vehicles.

Children age 5 years old and younger are exempt and will not need to wear a mask, unless they are in kindergarten.

Others exempt include those with a medical condition, a mental health condition, or disability that makes it unreasonable for the individual to maintain a face covering.

Masks can be removed temporarily when students and staff are exercising (including recess), eating, drinking, singing, public speaking, playing musical instruments and receiving personal care or medical service.

Masks are strongly recommended outdoors when it is not possible to maintain social distancing.

There are different parameters for pre-K and child care spaces.

post_text:
The Ortonville School thanks all of our families who joined us for our Distance Learning Material Pick-up. Thanks, too, to the Ortonville Police Department, Fire Department, BSC Sheriffs and MN State Patrol who came to show support and share smiles. We are blessed to be part of such a supportive community which comes together for others.
Our mission has always been to ensure the future by creating lifelong learners. There have been a lot of tears during this planning time because we miss your children, but our commitment and mission has never wavered. While every role has been different, all staff have worked together, bravely and boldly to take on the unknown and further help our students and district. We will recharge this weekend and on Monday our commitment will remain the same: to help your children learn and grow! Parents, you are not in this alone! Our school team is here because we want to help your children. We will continue to do that in this new way, until we can do it again in our classrooms.
#JKE #OHS #TrojanNation
#AloneTogether #WeLoveOurCommunity

post_text:
Per the MSHSL on March 25, 2020:

Effective immediately and continuing until the Governor of Minnesota has lifted his school closure declaration (May 4th):
• All participation in MSHSL spring activities at all member schools is suspended.
• Participation includes, but is not limited to, competitions, training, practices, scrimmages, and contests.

No decisions regarding the cancellation of spring activities have been made at this time.

The suspension of participation includes fine arts activities and athletics and the following events remain suspended indefinitely:
• Speech Section and State Tournaments
• Music Contests
• Visual Arts Competitions and State Festival
• MSHSL State Robotics Tournament
• MSHSL Clay Target State Tournament

Additional information will be provided as it becomes available and as decisions are made by the MSHSL.

Ortonville Superintendent Search
The Ortonville School Board is conducting a search for a new superintendent. The school board contracted with the Minnesota School Boards Association (MSBA) to provide guidance and assist with the search. The school board met November 25, 2019, to plan the search. An online survey is available for staff and community members to fill out beginning November 25, 2019, to 11:59 p.m. December 14, 2019. To complete the online version of the Ortonville Public Schools Superintendent Search Survey, click https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/Ortonville The school board application deadline for this position is January 27, 2020.

post_text:
Be Here. Every Minute Matters. Here are some practical tips for parents to support regular school attendance:

1. Make sure your student keeps a regular bedtime and establish a morning routine.
2. Lay out clothes and pack backpacks the night before.
3. Ensure your student goes to school every day unless he/she is truly sick.
4. Avoid scheduling vacations or doctor’s appointments when school is in session. If you have to schedule an appointment during a school day, please try to only take your child out of school for the actual appointment.
5. Talk to teachers and counselors for advice if your student feels anxious about going to school.
6. Develop back-up plans for getting to school if something comes up. Call on a family member, neighbor, or another parent to take your student to school.

If you shop at Shutterfly and would like to further help Ortonville Public School this holiday season, we’ve made it super easy (and fun) to support us! You can shop through our Shutterfly Storefront to create Christmas cards, photo books, keepsakes, gifts, home décor and more—and Shutterfly will donate 8% to our school.

Every little bit helps, and together, we can reach our goal of $500.00. Please help us spread the word by sharing this post! Happy Holidays and happy shopping!

www.opstrojans.shutterflystorefront.com

post_text: 3D printers are becoming popular not only in industry but also in homes. Mrs. Kunde’s Computer Technology 7th and 8th grade classes and Mrs. Gustafson’s 6th grade class gained skills in creating and designing their own “Jack-o-Lantern Can” 3D project using the Tinkercad program. Each student’s project was then printed out on the 3D printer. Students enjoyed seeing the tea light candle glow inside of their very own creation!
